    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.7.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNA\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 20.04.4 LTS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKitty 0.15.0/konsole 19.12.3\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nappimage\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nnvim --clean\r\n`:lua vim.fn.jobwait({vim.fn.jobstart([[stat / -c \"NAME=%n]] .. string.char(0) .. '\"')})`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nWhen the above command is ran from a shell (injecting the null character in shell instead), I receive the following output\r\n```sh\r\n$ export NULL=$(echo -e \"\\0\") && stat / -c \"NAME=%n${NULL}\"\r\nNAME=/\r\n```\r\nI would expect `vim.fn.jobstart` to accept commands with a valid null character in the string (as ascii character `\\0` is a valid ascii character).\r\n\r\nI wonder if this has to do with how char arrays are handled in C land in vim?\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nReceive the following error\r\n```\r\nE5108: Error executing lua Vim:E475: Invalid argument: expected String or List                                                                                \r\nstack traceback:\r\n        [C]: in function 'jobstart'\r\n        [string \":lua\"]:1: in main chunk\r\nPress ENTER or type command to continue\r\n```\r\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
